<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1544]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,385,1231,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">Natural history</emphasis>
: A large sample was collected in January (
<specimenCount box="[879,1049,1231,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" type="generic">
<number box="[879,922,1232,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" value="107.0">107</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
) on a single unidentified tree in a wet elfin forest located between 
<quantity box="[521,677,1268,1292]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" unit="m" value="2200.0" valueMax="2300.0" valueMin="2100.0">2100–2300 m</quantity>
(F. Génier, 
<collectionCode box="[813,898,1268,1292]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">CMNC</collectionCode>
, personal communication). The 
<typeStatus box="[1264,1312,1269,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,272,1304,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Macrodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[151,272,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">M. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is “La Paz, 
<quantity box="[435,530,1303,1328]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.65" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" unit="m" value="3650.0">3650 m</quantity>
”, but probably corresponds to some a site along the road from La Paz to Cochabamba, because the 
<typeStatus box="[449,497,1341,1365]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296">type</typeStatus>
of vegetation near La Paz is much different from “Yungas” forest. “Los Yungas” is a geographic region located between the northeast of La Paz department and part of Cochabamba and Santa Cruz departments, on mountain slopes between 
<number box="[655,697,1412,1437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" value="600.0">600</number>
and 
<quantity box="[762,853,1412,1437]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="296" unit="m" value="2500.0">2500 m</quantity>
elevation where the hot-humid climate promotes exuberant vegetative growth.
</paragraph>
